      "originalText": "Django/ FastAPI",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "QUjS1UWouXRnT0JmQpNNr",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2022.7325484625815,
      "y": 7200.596886461252,
      "width": 1485,
      "height": 4650,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bFM",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1855178497,
      "version": 5,
      "versionNonce": 229841139,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775229075296,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Good question—this is a **core concept behind FastAPI’s performance**.\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 What are I/O-bound tasks?\n\n**I/O (Input/Output) tasks** are operations where your program spends most of its time **waiting for external systems**, not using CPU.\n\n### Examples of I/O tasks:\n\n* 🌐 Calling external APIs\n* 🗄️ Database queries\n* 📁 Reading/writing files\n* 🔌 Network requests\n* 📨 Sending emails\n\n👉 Key idea:\n**CPU is idle, just waiting for response**\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Simple analogy\n\nThink of ordering food:\n\n* CPU task → Cooking yourself 🍳\n* I/O task → Waiting for delivery 🚚\n\n👉 During waiting, you can do something else — and that’s where FastAPI shines.\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Problem with traditional frameworks (like Django/Flask)\n\nThey are mostly **synchronous (blocking)**:\n\n```\nRequest 1 → DB call (wait...) → Response\n           ❌ server blocked\n```\n\n👉 While waiting:\n\n* That thread is **blocked**\n* Cannot handle other requests\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 How FastAPI makes I/O fast\n\nFastAPI is built on:\n\n* Starlette\n* Uvicorn\n* Python async (`async/await`)\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Core idea: **Non-blocking async I/O**\n\nInstead of waiting, FastAPI does:\n\n```\nRequest 1 → DB call (await)\n          → switch to Request 2\n          → switch to Request 3\n```\n\n👉 It uses an **event loop** (like Node.js)\n\n---\n\n## 🔁 Execution Flow\n\n### Traditional (Blocking)\n\n```\n[Request A] ----waiting---- done\n(no other work happens)\n```\n\n### FastAPI (Async)\n\n```\n[Request A] ---waiting---\n              ↘\n         [Request B] ---waiting---\n              ↘\n         [Request C]\n```\n\n👉 One thread handles **many requests concurrently**\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Example\n\n### ❌ Blocking code (Django style)\n\n```python\ndef get_data():\n    data = requests.get(\"https://api.com\")  # blocks\n    return data.json()\n```\n\n---\n\n### ✅ FastAPI async code\n\n```python\nimport httpx\n\nasync def get_data():\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        response = await client.get(\"https://api.com\")\n    return response.json()\n```\n\n👉 `await` =\n➡️ “pause this task, do something else meanwhile”\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Why it is faster\n\n### 1. Better CPU utilization\n\n* No idle waiting\n* Handles multiple requests in same thread\n\n### 2. High concurrency\n\n* 1 thread → 1000+ requests (I/O heavy)\n\n### 3. Less memory usage\n\n* No need for many threads/processes\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Important clarification (INTERVIEW GOLD ⚡)\n\n👉 FastAPI is **NOT faster for everything**\n\n| Task Type | FastAPI Benefit    |\n| --------- | ------------------ |\n| I/O-bound | ✅ Huge improvement |\n| CPU-bound | ❌ No major gain    |\n\n---\n\n## 🔥 CPU-bound example\n\n* Image processing\n* Data compression\n* ML models\n\n👉 For these, use:\n\n* Celery (background jobs)\n* multiprocessing\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 One-line summary\n\n👉 **I/O tasks = waiting tasks**\n👉 **FastAPI = handles waiting smartly using async → higher concurrency → faster apps**\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Real-world connection (your backend work)\n\nFor your system:\n\n* Xero API calls → I/O ✅\n* DB queries → I/O ✅\n* Sending notifications → I/O ✅\n\n👉 FastAPI would **scale better under load** vs traditional blocking approach\n\n---\n\nIf you want next:\nI can explain **how ASGI vs WSGI works internally with request flow diagram** (very useful for interviews).\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Good question—this is a **core concept behind FastAPI’s performance**.\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 What are I/O-bound tasks?\n\n**I/O (Input/Output) tasks** are operations where your program spends most of its time **waiting for external systems**, not using CPU.\n\n### Examples of I/O tasks:\n\n* 🌐 Calling external APIs\n* 🗄️ Database queries\n* 📁 Reading/writing files\n* 🔌 Network requests\n* 📨 Sending emails\n\n👉 Key idea:\n**CPU is idle, just waiting for response**\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Simple analogy\n\nThink of ordering food:\n\n* CPU task → Cooking yourself 🍳\n* I/O task → Waiting for delivery 🚚\n\n👉 During waiting, you can do something else — and that’s where FastAPI shines.\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Problem with traditional frameworks (like Django/Flask)\n\nThey are mostly **synchronous (blocking)**:\n\n```\nRequest 1 → DB call (wait...) → Response\n           ❌ server blocked\n```\n\n👉 While waiting:\n\n* That thread is **blocked**\n* Cannot handle other requests\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 How FastAPI makes I/O fast\n\nFastAPI is built on:\n\n* Starlette\n* Uvicorn\n* Python async (`async/await`)\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Core idea: **Non-blocking async I/O**\n\nInstead of waiting, FastAPI does:\n\n```\nRequest 1 → DB call (await)\n          → switch to Request 2\n          → switch to Request 3\n```\n\n👉 It uses an **event loop** (like Node.js)\n\n---\n\n## 🔁 Execution Flow\n\n### Traditional (Blocking)\n\n```\n[Request A] ----waiting---- done\n(no other work happens)\n```\n\n### FastAPI (Async)\n\n```\n[Request A] ---waiting---\n              ↘\n         [Request B] ---waiting---\n              ↘\n         [Request C]\n```\n\n👉 One thread handles **many requests concurrently**\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Example\n\n### ❌ Blocking code (Django style)\n\n```python\ndef get_data():\n    data = requests.get(\"https://api.com\")  # blocks\n    return data.json()\n```\n\n---\n\n### ✅ FastAPI async code\n\n```python\nimport httpx\n\nasync def get_data():\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:\n        response = await client.get(\"https://api.com\")\n    return response.json()\n```\n\n👉 `await` =\n➡️ “pause this task, do something else meanwhile”\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Why it is faster\n\n### 1. Better CPU utilization\n\n* No idle waiting\n* Handles multiple requests in same thread\n\n### 2. High concurrency\n\n* 1 thread → 1000+ requests (I/O heavy)\n\n### 3. Less memory usage\n\n* No need for many threads/processes\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Important clarification (INTERVIEW GOLD ⚡)\n\n👉 FastAPI is **NOT faster for everything**\n\n| Task Type | FastAPI Benefit    |\n| --------- | ------------------ |\n| I/O-bound | ✅ Huge improvement |\n| CPU-bound | ❌ No major gain    |\n\n---\n\n## 🔥 CPU-bound example\n\n* Image processing\n* Data compression\n* ML models\n\n👉 For these, use:\n\n* Celery (background jobs)\n* multiprocessing\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 One-line summary\n\n👉 **I/O tasks = waiting tasks**\n👉 **FastAPI = handles waiting smartly using async → higher concurrency → faster apps**\n\n---\n\n# 🔹 Real-world connection (your backend work)\n\nFor your system:\n\n* Xero API calls → I/O ✅\n* DB queries → I/O ✅\n* Sending notifications → I/O ✅\n\n👉 FastAPI would **scale better under load** vs traditional blocking approach\n\n---\n\nIf you want next:\nI can explain **how ASGI vs WSGI works internally with request flow diagram** (very useful for interviews).\n",
